First, the responses of OSiNDs toward other kinds of tetracycline derivatives were carefully studied due to their highly similar structure (Fig. 4
                        ). One can see that the emission of DOC exhibits its characteristic peak at 517 nm under the assistance of OSiNDs, while other TCs showed weak fluorescence or no fluorescence. This phenomenon might be ascribed to the higher absorbance of the OSiNDs/DOC complex at 365 nm compared with the mixture of OSiNDs and other TCs, leading to a more efficient FRET process from OSiNDs to DOC and consequently enhanced the self-fluorescence of DOC at 517 nm (Fig. S15). As for MOC, no obvious fluorescence was obtained at 517 nm, which was ascribed to its non-fluorescence even in solid state. For the emission centered at 448 nm, the fluorescence of DOC was weaker than other TCs, suggesting its highest quenching efficiency which enhanced the possibility of the discrimination towards DOC (Fig. 5
                        A). Simultaneously, the signal of F517/F448 was performed to obtain quantitative identification among TCs. As shown in Fig. 5B, the signal of DOC was much higher than other four kinds of TCs with a statistically significant difference (p < 0.005, n = 4), indicating its easily distinguished detection performance from other TCs.
